{
  "108.1": {
    "score": 9,
    "evidence": "The codebase demonstrates an excellent understanding of the Next.js App Router server/client boundary. Pages like `app/arena/page.tsx` and `app/agents/page.tsx` are Server Components that fetch data in parallel and pass minimal required props to Client Components like `<ArenaBuilder>` and `<AgentsCatalog>`. The copy system is resolved server-side and provided via context, keeping the client bundle clean."
  },
  "108.2": {
    "score": 9,
    "evidence": "Client-side state is highly cohesive and well-encapsulated in custom hooks. `lib/use-bout.ts` manages a complex streaming state machine, including a clever 'pending message' buffer to simulate a thinking delay. `lib/use-bout-reactions.ts` implements optimistic UI updates with automatic rollback on API failure. There is no unnecessary global state."
  },
  "108.3": {
    "score": 9,
    "evidence": "Loading and error states are handled comprehensively. Route-level loading is managed with skeleton screens in `loading.tsx` files (e.g., `app/arena/loading.tsx`). The `Arena` component handles specific streaming errors gracefully, including a dedicated `<RateLimitUpgradePrompt>` for 429s. Empty states are present for lists like recent bouts and agent catalogs."
  },
  "108.4": {
    "score": 8,
    "evidence": "Good accessibility practices are evident. Semantic HTML is used throughout (`<main>`, `<article>`, `<nav>`). A 'skip to content' link is present in `app/layout.tsx`. Interactive elements have appropriate ARIA attributes (e.g., `aria-expanded` in `SiteHeader`, `aria-label` in `AskThePit`). Modals implement escape-key listeners to close. Focus trapping in modals could be slightly improved, but overall it is very solid."
  },
  "108.5": {
    "score": 9,
    "evidence": "Responsive design is thoughtfully implemented using Tailwind utility classes. The `SiteHeader` includes a mobile hamburger menu. Wide data tables like `LeaderboardTable` use `overflow-x-auto` to prevent breaking the mobile viewport. The project even includes specific E2E tests (`tests/e2e/mobile-responsive.spec.ts`) to assert no horizontal overflow on mobile devices."
  },
  "108.6": {
    "score": 8,
    "evidence": "Performance is prioritized through the architecture. Heavy data fetching and copy resolution occur on the server. Non-critical client features are code-split, such as the `AskThePit` component which is dynamically imported via `next/dynamic` in `components/ask-the-pit-lazy.tsx`. OG images are generated dynamically on the edge."
  },
  "108.7": {
    "score": 8,
    "evidence": "The brutalist, dark-mode aesthetic is applied consistently across all pages. Reusable UI primitives like `PitButton` and `PitBadge` encapsulate common styles. There is a strong, consistent typographic scale (e.g., uppercase tracking for labels) and consistent use of border and background opacities (`border-foreground/70`, `bg-black/60`)."
  }
}
